On the occasion of the most anticipated meeting in years, Federal Reserve policymakers will spend two days this week around a 27-foot Mahonhono table to decide whether it was time to raise a key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Above them, at one end of the central bank's meeting room, a U.S. mural will be glimpsed.
The map is meant to recall that Janet L. Yellen, the Fed President, and his colleagues must put the economic interests of the nation above everything else.
The central bank was given a double burden from Congress: maximizing the employment rate in the US and maintaining price stability.
But since the big economic crisis, Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third task could be factor X in a decision too difficult to predict, which will be announced on Tuesday, and which will determine whether the U.S. economy is ready to be stripped of the unprecedented stimulus offered by the near-zero short-term interest rate in place from the end of 2008.
Even though most of the data points to a strong growing economy, the recent stir in global financial markets could scare Fed officials already cautious of adding volatility by increasing the benchmark to federal funds - even by a quarter of a percentage point alone.
“Obviously, the labour market and inflation will be the first and main aspects they will pursue,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think that if they were to look for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, the growing uncertainty in the global market is enough to give them arguments to wait,” she said.
There is no consensus on the decision that the Fed will make, it itself causing instability in the financial market.
About half of economists recently surveyed by Bloomberg anticipated an increase in interest rates this week.
But financial markets expect the Fed to delay, with a key indicator showing that the likelihood of growth is only 30 percent.
That would indicate a fall on the stock exchange if the Fed raises the interest rate, unless policymakers would mitigate the blow promising that it would take a long time to go down to the next increase.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average climbed 228.89 points, or 1.4 percent to 16,599.85.
The momentum was triggered by expectations that Fed decision makers will keep the interest rate stable this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be surprising for the Fed to raise the interest rate at this time," Lonski said.
If the Fed decision makers did this, "it would have to act in depth in their policies to avoid panic in financial markets."
Other experts said an interest rate hike would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty over when the Fed would act.
Just a month ago, the Fed appeared to be on track to be on the verge of 0.25 percent this month, the first small step towards slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of U.S. recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that he expected an interest rate hike this year despite high objections by liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, labour market growth has been solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest percentage in more than seven years and close to the level considered by the Fed as total employment.
Wage gains showed signs of growth.
And although inflation continued not to reach the central bank's annual target, Fed policymakers claimed a key reason was the temporary effect of the sharply falling oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the labor market tension," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began going into fibrillation later this month after China devalued its currency.
Industrial media Dow Jones fell 16 percent below the record high reached in May as investors feared the slowdown in the Chinese economy would drag down world growth.
The market has somewhat recoiled this month, with the Dow now being about 10 percent below the May high.
For Fed decision makers, the hustle and bustle in the market adds to the complex calculation of the moment of interest rate rise.
“Without what has happened in the financial markets and news of weakening the Chinese economy in recent weeks, it would be firmer at the meeting,” Stephen D said. Oliner, an experienced researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and former Fed official.
Now he expects at least a month to better manage the effects.
“There is a lot of uncertainty that the impact on the U.S. economy will be and they almost don’t have data on which to be based on after the events in China,” Oliner said.
The well-being of the global economy is not one of the major interests of the Fed, so it should not be considered in decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed has become the global monetary authority.
In recent years, the central bank's influence has been huge.
The mere allusion of the then president, Ben S. Bernanke, in 2013, that the Fed could "narrow" its monetary expansion triggered earthquake in global markets.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed officials are expected not only to monitor progress in other areas, but also consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the world economy.
His decision-making process is "more art than science," said Zachary Karabell, head of the global strategy department at the welfare management firm Evestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., said this month that "the Fed has an oversized reaction history to changes in the financial market that seem unrelated to the economic bases."
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Commission, a decision-making body that advocated the interest rate rise, gave the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
A financial crisis that affected Asia led the Fed to reduce the benchmark rate by 0.75 percent in three meetings, "despitating the implications with the possibility of limited identification for US development," Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials backtracked on those declines.
The Fed should only pose the issue of financial stability first in the event of a major crisis, such as the 2008 market earthquake, Adam S said. Posen, former member of the Bank of England interest rate committee.
The last hectic period does not rise to that level, he said.
“We certainly don’t want to end up fearing an interest rate hike because markets have been upset,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still holds the double mandate and does not mention financial stability, and until something changes in this regard, I don't think it should take action prematurely.
