Weight reduction surgery could be useful in mild-obese diabetics
The benefits of weight-reducing surgery in people with mild obesity with type 2 diabetes could hold for at least five years, according to a new study.
It's still premature to tell if diabetics with mild obesity live longer after weight loss surgery than those undergoing nonsurgical treatments.
"It takes a long time to centralize mortality data," said Dr. Robin Blackstone, a specialist in obesity surgery, who wrote an article about the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight loss operations, also called bariatric surgery, use various methods to shrink the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the body’s ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been shown to be effective in the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most of the studies have been conducted on people with morbid obesity, with a body mass index (BMI) 35 or higher.
BMI, a unit of weight measurement in relation to height, is considered normal in the range of 18.5-24.9.
The BMI value of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight and people with BMI above 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI by accessing: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at the General Min-Sheng Hospital in Taiwan used the close data after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and gastrectomy in the sleeve - in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
Average BMI in people who underwent surgery decreased from 31 to 24.5 to the end of the fifth year in the study.
Meanwhile, BMI in people who received nonsurgical treatments against diabetes remained almost at the same level, namely 29.
Of those who underwent surgery, diabetes mellitus was completely cured in 36% and partly in 28 percent.
In the group treated by medical methods, by comparison, diabetes mellitus was completely cured at only 1% and partially in only 2% of subjects.
In addition, blood pressure control, triglycerides and “bad” LDL cholesterol “were generally better in the surgical group,” the authors concluded.
The researchers also monitored blood levels of hemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood glucose levels over time.
Researchers write that the optimal level of hemoglobin A1c is below 7%.
After surgery, the average level of hemoglobin A1c dropped from about 9% to about 6%.
But in the group treated by medical methods, it was maintained at about 8%.
But this improved “gluemic control” – reflected by improved hemoglobin levels A1c – did not reduce the mortality rate to five years, according to chief scientist Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared to the group with gastrectomy in the sleeve, the bypass surgery group lost more weight (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), recorded more considerable decreases in BMI (7.4 compared to 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1% vs. 2.1%) and showed a higher probability of complete remission of diabetes (46.9%).
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of heavyweight people in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, says Blackstone, of the University of Arizona, Faculty of Medicine - Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery were about 29 percent less likely to die after 15 years, compared to a group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a survival benefit in patients who underwent surgery, Blackstone said it was an optimistic aspect for people with BMI below 35 interested in the procedure.
"This is where this work is critical because it states that this surgery is safe in the lower BMI group," without increasing risk of death or kidney disease, she states.
Blackstone added that patients and their doctors should start taking the weight seriously then the patient's BMI reaches 27-30.
"I think we're waiting too long to urge people to take this seriously," she said.
I think that once they have accumulated these genetic changes that short-circuited their bodies predisposing them to obesity and diabetes, it is extremely hard to return to normal.
