Friendship is at the heart of the struggle towards the success of this challenge.
A recent study of more than 2000 high school students who were experiencing symptoms of depression concluded that if the patient is surrounded by enough friends “with a healthy mood”, his chances of recovery double.
Equally, for people who are not depressed, a circle of healthy mental friends halves the likelihood of mental disorders.
Of course, in order for friendship to have an effect, it must first be accessible.
In this era of communication dominated by social networks, where emphasis is placed on style and not on substance, the immediateness of the response often takes precedence over meaningful contact.
Our digital lives have doubled the need to create the appearance of a strong personality, open to fun and success, even if it is in reality it is the dominion.
This superficial success is dominated by what psychologists call extrinsic values; money, image, social status, all at the cost of intrinsic values - our inner desire for personal development and friendship - that further affects our mental health.
The billionaire inventor of a video game recently explained that money really doesn't buy happiness.
The beauty of Friends was that he turned attention to this idea.
The characters were not defined by the workplace but by their own personality, which they showed by interacting as friends.
The humor of Joey and Chandler's frequent hugs, the moments when they look at football in comfortable chairs and Ross' passion for Rachel came from the fact that men are known to associate with this situation, even though they often shy away from completely exploring their feelings.
As one social worker explained to me: ..."my role of listening to people with a suicidal and depressed tendency showed how even the smallest interactions with friends can make a difference."
Often, people who turn to us don't feel able to talk to friends.
The old saying to fend for yourself is strong, as is the feeling of being perceived as a weak person if you talk openly about problems.
Friends is one of the series that comes to mind when I try to provide more mechanisms of long-term psychological adaptation.
The series highlighted the small moments of friendship between men.
As much as objective, external intervention helps through the phone, people who arrive in moments of despair, long-term support comes from family and close friends.
Thus, if you are attending this weekend at Comedy Central’s FriendsFest, with the complete rendering of the film sets to celebrate the event, why not invite your friends for a coffee in Central Perk.
Or, even better, if you see someone alone in Starbucks, smile and say hello.
You never know what difference your friendship might make.
