"Ziarul de Iași", who witnessed the efforts to search the family of origin after some extremely vague clues, witnessed these meetings that practically break your heart.
Reporting reporters, the emotions of the moments, the statements of those involved, their reactions are downright moving and overwhelming.
The story of Crina begins 20 years ago in the town of Ruginoasa, when she was only two months old.
Then, due to a health problem, the girl had to be admitted to the hospital, in the city.
Home there began to be misunderstandings between the parents, and the mother had to leave the home.
He decided to keep the girl, and send me away from home.
He stopped the girl, and I didn't know anything since.
"When I found out she was in the hospital, it was too late," recalled Alina, the girl's biological mother.
Crina was admitted with her grandmother to the municipal hospital in Pașcani, and then the girl’s father, Costică Balcan, went to work in the city of Alexandria, Teleorman County.
Their lives would separate forever.
They couldn't find Crina in the hospital
After admission, Crina's father went to work in another locality, and returned after six months.
Meanwhile, the girl was transferred to the hospital in Iasi, and the father, when he returned, did not find her.
I think it's been almost nine months since the girl was in the hospital.
"He may have thought he was abandoned," says a granddaughter of the family.
Due to financial problems, the grandmother could not come with Crina to Iasi, and the girl remained in the care of doctors.
Because no one was interested in the child’s fate during this time, she was taken over by the General Directorate of Social Assistance and Child Protection Iasi, who then gave her to care for the Bucium Placement Center.
There were years when abandonment and adoption were more easily regulated than in Romania today.
At the Bucium Center she was found by the Italian Salvadore and his wife, a couple from Palermo who wanted to have their child but did not succeed.
They fell in love with the blonde Crina, and after some time she would move permanently with them to Italy.
The little girl had already done almost two years, while the adoption formalities lasted.
When I saw Crina, I felt it was our face.
"It's like my wife gave her life," Salvadore, the foster father, tells us, while catching the girl's filthy hand in his hand.
In the country, the parents of Crina, Alina and Costică, continued separately the searches, each where they could.
The father asked the authorities in Ruginoasa, but received no answer where his child might be.
The police then told her that she may be deceased, but in Iasi the parents found out what really happened to their daughter.
When I looked for her here, they told me at the court she was away in Italy in Palermo.
And conditions to look for her I didn't have.
We prayed to God to be well.
I thought of her in all the years that passed, but there were no possibilities to walk, to find her.
"It's hard," tells us with tears in the eyes of the biological mother of Crina.
But even if the years passed, the parents in Ruginoasa were not forgotten.
In Italy, Salvadore and his wife explained to the girl where she came from and that her past connects her to Romania.
I was little when I found out.
I think I was five or six years old.
I reacted like a child, I was curious.
"I wanted to meet my parents in Romania", confesses Crina.
Her dream was coming to come true.
In March this year, Chief Commissioner Romica Ichim, director of the Regional Center for Drug Prevention, Evaluation and Counseling Iasi, was contacted by an acquaintance from Italy, who explained Salvadore’s desire to find the biological family of Crina.
And the search started only from a name.
After the request we had from our partners in Italy, we started the first steps.
I received only one name, Balcan Costică, then the locality, Ruginoasa.
Shortly after, I had an activity with the town hall there, and I could ask if there was the name received in the locality.
Then they gave me some indications, only that the person found was not the one wanted.
"It lasted about a month before we found the girl's biological father," explains Chief Commissioner Romica Ichim.
In total, more than three months they took the authorities to find Costica and Alina, especially since each had their domicile in another locality.
We started the steps sometime in March, and in June-July we completed the identification of the biological parents and the discussions.
"Then we decided that in September there will be a first meeting," added Romică Ichim.
In the past weekend, Alina and Costică saw their lost girl in the hallways of the Iasi hospital 20 years ago.
The father, excited, could barely contain his tears, and his hands trembled incessantly.
He's barely changing a few words with those around him.
A week before the meeting, he couldn't even sleep.
He was still excited, shaking.
"To see your child after so many years, it's something," says a granddaughter, who came with Costica from Ruginoasa.
Crina's meeting with mother and biological brother
In discussions with his daughter, who is going to study at a well-rated university in Italy, Costică Balcan told him, among other things, that if he wants to return to him, in the village, to come quietly: he can give him some sheep, goats, to find a boy from the village and to encroach a household.
My mother is also excited, she cries, and she hardly thinks that something like this can happen to her.
I am very excited.
I never thought something like this could happen.
I've seen such cases on TV, I've been thinking about it in these years, I've hoped, but I didn't think I could be like that too.
They are very big emotions.
If he could forgive me.
I hope we visit in the future.
"I hope we can keep a bond," says with great tears on Alina's cheeks, the mother of Crina, as she holds a napkin tightly.
He hides his tears, happiness, because he will soon see her face after so long.
On the other hand, Crina, who will turn in just a few days, this month, 20 years, tries to calm down like an emotional child.
She doesn’t know what to expect, but she has sketched a vague idea of her biological parents.
He thinks they are young, but now before the meeting they try to gather their thoughts, because she has a lot to say, but nothing to reproach.
My parents are two mothers and two fathers.
But my parents are, after all, the ones who raised me.
It will be a beautiful meeting, a wonderful experience.
"I hope to have a beautiful memory with them, because now there are so many things to say," Crina confesses.
The first family reunion in Iasi
In Unirii Square, under the sky of the beginning of autumn, the family of Ruginoasa unites again its destiny with their daughter from Palermo.
Crina is now 20 years old, she finishes high school, after the Italian school model, but she can start a new chapter with Alina and Costica, her biological parents.
No longer separate borders or countries, but only a barrier: that of language.
Over which, with the help of a translator, an Italian owner of the local in the center of Iasi, they passed easily.
Those who have managed to make this meeting possible say that it is the first event of this kind made, and that in the future, if the opportunity arises, they will do it again.
It is the first event of its kind organized, of such an emotional charge, and I am glad to be a success.
We, at the Center, have different activities, and most of the time we are associated as an institution that deals only with consumers, people addicted to drugs.
But we're trying to restore to society something good back.
"If I am asked for such an event again, I will do it with great love," says Romică Ichim, director of the Regional Center for Drug Prevention, Evaluation and Counseling in Iasi.
Behind him, the Balcans, with Crina in the middle, walk away telling stories.
I understand: they have a lot to tell each other.
