With a sentence, however detestable they are.
Forget the stupid success stories that are delivered to you daily in newspapers and on television.
Look carefully at the figure of this man.
Do you want to know how he succeeded in life, how, today, he heard of it an entire world?
It's simple.
He worked all his life to be someone.
That's what he did.
Constantin Brancusi was born on February 19, 1876, in Hobița, a small village in Peeștișani, Gorj County, at the foot of the Carpathians.
He is the fifth child of Maria and Radu Nicolae Brancusi.
Although he came from a wealthy peasant family, Brancusi leads a modest life, but one from which he would collect the landmarks that will guide his late artistic vision.
Remembering his childhood and the places where he grew up, the artist would confess, in a meeting with Petre Ţuţea, from Paris, from 1933: "Basily then was beautiful and harmonious".
For millennia, people have been happily leading a patriarchal life.
Everything passed quietly from one season to another.
And do you know why things have changed?
The civilisation of the great city has reached us.
But Brancusi’s childhood was far from an idyllic one.
One of the moments spent in these first years of life is extremely suggestive of the combination of purity and violence that have characterized the future sculptor for years in his native town.
The moment is reproduced in the work "Brancusi. A biography", written by Alexandru Buican.
In 1879, Constantin Brâncuși was 3 years old.
In the autumn of that year, when the țuica was made "la cazan", following those who taste the liquid to see if the process is going properly, Brancusi catches a moment of general inattention.
He fills his palms with a bitch and drinks breathlessly.
Falls in sleep almost instantly.
The first people notice only after a few minutes.
The mother panicked, then into hysteria, thinking her son had died.
In the evening, when the father, Radu, returns from the vineyard accompanied by the fiddlers, he sees from afar the desperate signs of those who wait for him with his breath.
The party immediately turns into mourning.
The father is already thinking about burial.
However, someone finds that it is good to call Baba Brindusa, doctor and servant of Brancusi.
The brandy checks the baby's breathing, then puts them under her godmother horse's ball, gathered from the whole world.
The child sneezes strongly.
The world is applauding.
While the boy is allowed to sleep on his drunkenness, for joy, the party with the fiddlers continues with even more force.
The next day, the father and son meet in the orchard.
Radu Brancusi has Constantin to collect some twigs and bring them to him.
The father puts his child upside down and, with the rods brought by the boy, beats him to remember.
And, while feeling the sting of the blows, little Brancusi has the revelation that the world can be viewed from a different perspective and that things around can appear overturned.
Especially the position of the sun, different from the well-known one, makes him wonder, as he would admit in his old age, if the star himself participated in his disorder.
Was the sun as troubled as his father had been?
